  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "note_10",
      "text": "WORKFLOW: categorical association (chi-square). When both variables are categories (not numbers), the question 'are they related?' is answered by the chi-squared test of independence. It cross-tabulates the two columns into a contingency table of observed counts, computes the counts you'd EXPECT if the variables were independent, and measures the gap: a large χ² (small p) means the observed pattern departs from independence — the variables are associated. Read the statistic, the degrees of freedom ((rows−1)×(cols−1)) and the p-value, then look at the table to see WHERE the association is (which cells are over- or under-represented). Yates' continuity correction is applied to 2×2 tables. Crucial caveat: the χ² approximation is unreliable when any EXPECTED count is below 5 (the node warns) — with small samples use Fisher's exact test instead. The test shows association, not direction or causation. Pearson (1900); Fisher (1922).",
      "x": 40,
      "y": 24,
      "width": 360,
      "height": 190
    }
